1 (G) IN DEVELOPING THE CLINICAL STAFFING PLAN, THE CLINICAL
2 STAFFING COMMITTEE SHALL CONSIDER:
3 (1) THE AVERAGE NUMBER OF PATIENTS ON EACH UNIT ON EACH
4 SHIFT DURING THE IMMEDIATELY PRECEDING YEAR AND RELEVANT INFORMATION
5 REGARDING PATIENT DISCHARGES, POTENTIAL ADMISSIONS, AND TRANSFERS;
6 (2) THE AVERAGE LEVEL OF ACUITY FOR PATIENTS ON EACH UNIT ON
7 EACH SHIFT DURING THE IMMEDIATELY PRECEDING YEAR AND THE
8 CORRESPONDING LEVEL OF NURSING CARE REQUIRED; AND
9 (3) AN ESTIMATE OF THE APPROPRIATE COMBINATION OF SKILL,
10 EXPERIENCE LEVEL, AND SPECIALTY CERTIFICATION OR TRAINING OF STAFF FOR
11 EACH UNIT ON EACH SHIFT THAT IS REQUIRED TO ADEQUATELY PROVIDE CARE.
12 19–389.
13 (A) ON OR BEFORE JANUARY 1 EACH YEAR, BEGINNING IN 2026, EACH
14 HOSPITAL SHALL:
15 (1) IMPLEMENT THE CLINICAL STAFFING PLAN ADOPTED UNDER §
16 19–388 OF THIS SUBTITLE; AND
17 (2) ASSIGN PERSONNEL TO EACH PATIENT CARE UNIT IN
18 ACCORDANCE WITH THE CLINICAL STAFFING PLAN.
19 (B) A REGISTERED NURSE, A LICENSED PRACTICAL NURSE, AN ANCILLARY
20 MEMBER OF THE FRONTLINE TEAM, OR AN APPLICABLE EXCLUSIVE
21 REPRESENTATIVE MAY SUBMIT A COMPLAINT TO THE CLINICAL STAFFING
22 COMMITTEE REGARDING ANY VARIATION WHERE PERSONNEL ASSIGNMENT IN A
23 PATIENT CARE UNIT IS NOT IN ACCORDANCE WITH THE ADOPTED CLINICAL
24 STAFFING PLAN.
25 (C) THE CLINICAL STAFFING COMMITTEE SHALL DETERMINE, BY A
26 MAJORITY VOTE, WHETHER A COMPLAINT HAS BEEN ADEQUATELY RESOLVED.
